According to the Kagera Regional Police Commander (RPC), no-one had died or been injured in the incidents that started on June 4, and all of which occurred during daytime.Calling on the people to remain calm, the Muleba District Commissioner, Engineer Richard Runyango, told reporters that the security and defence committee was scheduled to make an assessment tour of the ward today.Meanwhile, the Lumasi Transit Camp in Ngara District has received about 150 refugees from neighbouring Democratic Republic of Congo and Burundi. The Ngara District Immigration Officer, Mr Amos Gideon, said the influx was recorded during the past two weeks. Some of the refugees from DRC said their flight had been prompted by nasty incidents triggered by political disturbances. We are making arrangements to transfer them to Mtenederi Refugee Camp in Kigoma Region, he said.